AxB (also written as A x B or A Ã— B) represents the Cartesian product of sets A and B. The Cartesian product is the set of all ordered pairs (a, b) where a is an element of A and b is an element of B.

A = {1, 2, 3}
B = {2, 3, 4}

AxB = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 2), (2, 3), (2, 4), (3, 2), (3, 3), (3, 4)}

BxA = {(2, 1), (2, 2), (2, 3), (3, 1), (3, 2), (3, 3), (4, 1), (4, 2), (4, 3)}

Now, let's find the intersection of AxB and BxA, which is the set of elements that are common to both AxB and BxA.

Intersection(AxB, BxA) = {(2, 2), (2, 3), (3, 2), (3, 3)}

Since AxB and BxA have different elements and their intersection is not equal to either AxB or BxA, we can conclude that AxB and BxA are not equal.
